   "source": [
    "Custom Sequences - Part 1 - Lecture"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "6c122782-1712-4f12-9273-bcea47a11310",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Creating our own Sequence Types\n",
    "\n",
    "We will cover Abstract Base Classes later\n",
    "At most basic, an immutable sequence type should support two things:\n",
    "- returning the length of the sequence (technically, we don't even really need that)\n",
    "- given an index, returning the elemnt at that index\n",
    "If an object provides this functionality then we should be able to:\n",
    "- retrieve elements by index using []\n",
    "- iterate through elements using Python loops (loops, comprehensions, ...)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "5f05425e-261f-4da0-9ad9-a7bce51e0d2e",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    " How Python does it\n",
    "\n",
    "Sequence types are iterables, but not all iterables are sequence types\n",
    "Sequence types, at min, implement the following methods\n",
    "\n",
    "__len__\n",
    "__getitem__\n",
    "\n",
    "At most basic, __getitem__ method takes single integer argument (index)\n",
    "However we may choose to handle a slice type argument\n",
    "How does this help iterating over sequences"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "51ff3d7b-5f64-4f21-8051-7d8c3766a507",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The __geitem__ method\n",
    "\n",
    "The __getitem__ method should  return an element of sequence based on specified index\n",
    "or raise an IndexError exception if index is out of bounds (and may support negative indices and slicing)\n",
    "Python's list object implements the __getitem__ method:\n",
    "\n",
    "my_list = ['a', 'b', 'c', 'd', 'e', 'f']\n",
    "my_list.__getitem__(0) -> 'a'\n",
    "my_list.__getitem__(1) -> 'b'\n",
    "my_list.__getitem__(-1) -> 'f'\n",
    "my_list.__getitem__(slice(None, None, -1)) -> ['f', 'e', 'd', 'c', 'b', 'a']\n",
    "\n",
    "If we specify an index that is out of bounds\n",
    "my_list.__getitem__(100) -> IndexError\n",
    "my_list.__getitem__(-100) -> IndexError\n",
    "\n",
    "All we need from __getitem__ is ability to\n",
    "- return element for a valid index\n",
    "- raise an IndexError exception for invalid index\n",
    "\n",
    "Also remember sequence indices start at 0 (we always know the index of first element in sequence)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "23ee1bbf-5f33-4ad7-b753-415d6fc7d359",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Implementing a for loop\n",
    "\n",
    "We know:\n",
    "sequence starts at 0\n",
    "__getitem__(i) will return element at index i\n",
    "__getitem__(i) will raise IndexError exception when i is out of bounds\n",
    "\n",
    "my_list = [0, 1, 2, 3, 4, 5]\n",
    "\n",
    "for item in my_list:\n",
    "    print(item **2)\n",
    "\n",
    "index = 0\n",
    "\n",
    "while True:\n",
    "    try:\n",
    "        item = my_list.__getitem__(index)\n",
    "    except IndexError:\n",
    "        break\n",
    "    print(item ** 2)\n",
    "    index += 1\n",
    "\n",
    "The point is that if object implements __getitem__ we can iterate through using a for loop or comprehension"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "880b8255-59ce-4bf4-8877-1ffe0bae09e4",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The __len__ method\n",
    "\n",
    "In general sequence types support the Python built-in function len()\n",
    "To support this all we need to do is implement __len__ method in our custom sequence type\n",
    "\n",
    "my_list = [0, 1, 2, 3, 4, 5]\n",
    "\n",
    "len(my_list) -> 6\n",
    "my_list.__len__() -> 6"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "c435b742-85a9-4576-a78b-d255dd823394",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Writing our own Custom Sequence Type\n",
    "\n",
    "To implement custom sequence type we implement\n",
    "__len__\n",
    "__getitem__\n",
    "\n",
    "At very least __getitem__ should:\n",
    "- retrun an element for valid index [0, len-1]\n",
    "- raise an IndexError exceptrion if index is out of bounds\n",
    "\n",
    "Additionally we can shoose to support\n",
    "- negative indices i < 0 -> i = length - 1\n",
    "- slicing handle slice objects as arguments to __getitem__ method"
   ]
  },
